# UI Styling Rules

## Precedence

Primary rule for UI composition and design-token usage.
For global conflict order, see `rules-index.mdc`.

## Scope and Non-Overlap

This rule focuses on UI composition and design-system usage.

- Covers: component choice, theme-token usage, variant usage, and loading-state patterns.
- Delegates motion and interaction governance to `frontend-motion-interaction-governance.mdc`:
  - `transition-all` bans and transition scoping
  - pseudo-clickable semantics and touch-target baselines
  - reduced-motion requirements
  - hero gradient presets and color-governance enforcement
  - media/performance animation constraints

When both files apply, follow this split to avoid duplicated or conflicting guidance.

## Extended Reference

For deeper examples and review checklists, use:

- `/.cursor/rules/ui-styling-playbook.mdc` (supplemental guidance)
- `/.cursor/rules/frontend-motion-interaction-governance.mdc` (motion/interaction baseline)

## Core Styling Framework

- Use Shadcn UI, Radix UI, and Tailwind CSS as the default stack.
- Build mobile-first responsive layouts with Tailwind utilities.
- Prefer composition with existing project UI primitives before custom wrappers.

## Theme-First Styling

Prefer semantic theme tokens and component variants for long-lived UI meaning.

- Use tokens for backgrounds, borders, text hierarchy, and statuses:
  `bg-background`, `bg-card`, `bg-muted`, `text-foreground`,
  `text-muted-foreground`, `border-border`, `text-destructive`, etc.
- Prefer built-in component variants over ad hoc class combinations:
  - `Button`: `default | secondary | outline | ghost | destructive`
  - `Alert`: `default | destructive`
  - `Badge`: supported project variants
- Local visual accents are allowed when bounded to a specific section and not used as global semantic state.
- **Headline emphasis**: use solid token text (`text-primary` for stressed words), not gradient clip-text on `h1`/`h2` copy — see `frontend-motion-interaction-governance.mdc` §4 (Headline emphasis).

### Color Quality

- Avoid raw `#000` / `#fff` — use design tokens or slightly tinted neutrals for a more natural feel.
- On colored backgrounds, tint neutral text toward the background hue instead of using raw gray (`text-gray-*`).
- Not every button should be `default` (primary) — use `ghost`, `outline`, `secondary` to create visual hierarchy.

### Good

```tsx
<Button>Upgrade</Button>
<Button variant="ghost">Cancel</Button>
<div className="border border-border bg-card text-card-foreground">...</div>
<div className="border border-destructive/20 bg-destructive/10 text-destructive">
  Failed
</div>
```

### Avoid

```tsx
<div className="bg-white text-black border-gray-200">...</div>
<div className="bg-[#000] text-[#fff]">...</div>
```

## Typography & Visual Hierarchy

- Vary font weight and size across headings, body, and labels to create clear hierarchy — avoid uniform type treatment.
- Use fluid font sizing (`text-sm` / `text-base` / `text-lg` / `text-xl` etc.) deliberately; do not apply the same size everywhere.
- Pair distinct heading styles with restrained body text for contrast.

## Layout Composition

- Do not nest cards inside cards — flatten the visual hierarchy.
- Avoid identical repeated card grids (same-sized cards with icon + heading + text) unless uniformity is the explicit intent.
- Create visual rhythm through varied spacing — tight groupings for related items, generous separations between sections. Monotonous equal spacing reads as unfinished.
- Do not center everything by default — left-aligned text with asymmetric layouts often reads more intentional.

## Component Usage Priority

Use project UI components first. Do not default to native controls for interactive UI.

### Use UI Components

- `<Button>` over `<button>`
- `<Input>` over `<input>`
- `<Textarea>` over `<textarea>`
- `<Select>` over native `<select>`
- `<Checkbox>`, `<RadioGroup>`, `<Switch>`
- `<Dialog>` / `<Sheet>`, `<Popover>` / `<DropdownMenu>`

### Native Exceptions (allowed)

- Structural semantics: `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<footer>`
- Special primitives: `<video>`, `<audio>`, `<canvas>`
- Form edge cases: hidden inputs and file inputs when required

### Import Convention

Import UI components from `@/components/ui/*`.

```tsx
import { Button } from '@/components/ui/button';
import { Input } from '@/components/ui/input';
import { Dialog, DialogContent, DialogTrigger } from '@/components/ui/dialog';
```

## Loading-State Rules

For async content, prefer skeleton-based loading over generic spinners-only patterns.

- Reuse existing skeletons first:
  - `@/components/ui/skeleton`
  - specialized skeletons (for example history/card/table variants)
- Skeleton layout should match final content structure.
- Keep loading-state branching explicit:
  - loading -> skeleton
  - error -> error state
  - empty -> empty state
  - success -> content

### Example

```tsx
if (loading) return <HistorySkeleton count={8} />;
if (error) return <ErrorState />;
if (!data?.length) return <EmptyState />;
return <Content data={data} />;
```

## Authoring Checklist

- [ ] UI controls use Shadcn/Radix primitives (or documented exception)
- [ ] Long-lived styling uses semantic tokens/variants — no raw `#hex`, `bg-white`, `text-black`
- [ ] Button variants create clear hierarchy (not all primary)
- [ ] Typography varies weight/size for heading vs body vs label
- [ ] No card-in-card nesting; spacing rhythm varies between sections
- [ ] Loading UX uses skeletons where data is asynchronous
- [ ] No duplicated motion/interaction rules introduced here; rely on `frontend-motion-interaction-governance.mdc`
